theorem buildLayer_neverFails (α : Type) [inst : DecidableEq α]
    [inst_1 : SampleableType α] [(spec α).DecidableEq]
    (preexisting_cache : (spec α).QueryCache) (n : ℕ)
    (leaves : List.Vector α (2 ^ (n + 1))) : HasEvalSPMF.NeverFail
      ((simulateQ randomOracle (buildLayer α n leaves)).run preexisting_cache) := by
  simp_rw [buildLayer]
  simp only [range_def, eq_mp_eq_cast, cast_eq, bind_pure]
  -- The above simplifications should reduce the problem to showing that
  -- the application of `mmap` with `query` will never fail.
  -- This is because `mmap` is a deterministic operation that will not cause
  -- the failure of the evaluation, and `query` is a well-defined operation
  -- in the oracle.
  -- However, Lean4 needs an explicit proof that the SPMF produced by `mmap` is never failing.
  -- This is trivially true because the output type is the same as the input type,
  -- and `mmap` will always return an element of the output type.
  -- Moreover, the evaluation of `mmap` is always successful because it is just a mapping.
  -- Therefore, we can conclude that the evaluation of `mmap` will never fail.
  -- The only potential issue is if the `query` function is not available,
  -- but since it is a part of the oracle, it is always available.
  -- Hence, the `mmap` operation will not fail.
  -- For a formal argument, we use the fact that if everything before the `mmap` is non-failing,
  -- then `mmap` will not introduce any failing cases because it is a deterministic function.
  -- Therefore, we can use the fact that the `mmap` of a non-failing SPMF is also non-failing.
  -- In the end, everything is like a chain of evaluations that are non-failing.
  refine' HasEvalSPMF.by_cases (_)
  <;> aesop
